05255nam a22009615i 9780520914520DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209145207 a10.1525/97805209145202doi  a(DE-B1597)544082  a(OCoLC)1149425185  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHC258.B76bS23 1991eb 7aHIS0370202bisacsh04a330.9423/932201 aSacks, David Harris, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Widening Gate :bBristol and the Atlantic Economy, 1450-1700 /cDavid Harris Sacks.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4cÂ©2023  a1 online resource (450 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe New Historicism: Studies in Cultural Poetics ;v1500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tTables -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Closed Arena and the Open Gate -- tPART I . OPENING THE WAY, 1450-1650 -- t1. Feats of Merchandise -- t2. Mere Merchants -- t3. Organizing the Society -- tPART 2. IN A WORSHIPFUL STATE, 1450-1650 -- t4. The Navel of the World -- t5. The Sanctification of Power -- t6. Little Businesses -- t7. Looking Backward -- tPART 3. THE CAPITALISM OF THE SPIRIT, 1650-1700 -- t8. A Shoemakers' Holiday -- t9. Registering the Pilgrimage -- t10. The Spirit World -- tConclusion: The Widening Gate of Capitalism -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe history of capitalism is not to be explained in mere economic terms. David Harris Sacks here demonstrates that the modern Western economy was ushered in by broad processes of social, political, and cultural change. His study of Bristol as it opened it gate to national politics and the Atlantic economy reveals capitalism to be not just a species of economic order but a distinct form of life, governed by its own ethical norms and cultural practices. Availing himself of the methods of ";thick description,"; socio-economic analysis, and political theory, Sacks examines the dynamics by which early modern Bristol moved from a medieval commercial economy to an early capitalist one. Throughout the period, the life of the city depended heavily on the successes of its great overseas merchants. But their quest for a monopoly of trade with the outside world, from the Atlantic seaboard to the Levant, came into conflict with the concerns of Bristol's artisans and retail shopkeepers. The battles of the two factions conditioned social and cultural developments in Bristol for two centuries. Locally, the conflict set the terms for developing conceptions of justice and authority. On a larger scale, it drew the community firmly into the great affairs of the realm and the wider world of expanding markets beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCapitalismzEnglandzBristolxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aartisans.  aatlantic economy.  aatlantic seaboard.  aauthority.  abristol.  acapitalism.  acity life.  acultural change.  acultural practices.  aearly capitalist economy.  aeconomic conditions.  aeconomic history.  aeconomics.  aenglish history.  aethical norms.  aethics.  ahistory of capitalism.  ajustice.  alevant.  amedieval commercial economy.  amerchandise.  amerchants.  amodern western economy.  amonopoly.  anational politics.  aoverseas merchants.  apilgrimage.  apolitical change.  apolitical theory.  aretail shopkeepers.  asocial change.  athick description.  aurban life.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052008449040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/